MLIST 85 348 150 3
MLIST 85 170 10 1
;
; Tablet
INUMBER 1860
NAME 1443
MISC
WEIGHT 1000
VOLUME 10
ARTICLE A
IFPREVERB LOOK -1
	CLEARVERB
	ECHO PLAYER There seems to be something written on the tablet.
ENDIF
IFPREVERB READ -1
	CLEARVERB
	IFVAR ITEMVAL1 = 1
		ECHO PLAYER Part the first:
		ECHO PLAYER The inscription reads:%c Herein is recorded the chronicle of Rakthaarn, lord of the frigid realms, so that his story might lie with his corpse. Thus it was that he was born a mortal man in the great and wondrous city of Mariel in ancient days past, when it still knew the joys and delights of the natural world. He journeyed forth, seeking honor and greatness for his kin, as was the fashion then. In his search for adventure, he wandered to the four corners of the world, and encountered much...
		ECHO PLAYER But he found nothing that would satisfy his desire. Then one day he came upon an ancient crone seated by a vine-covered hut. He told her of his search for adventure, and of the things he had discovered, and she chuckled, and said that nothing short of the gods themselves could satisfy his lust. He left the area thoughtfully, thinking on what she had said, and realized that she was right. So, he began to seek out the gods.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL1 = 2
		ECHO PLAYER Part the second:
		ECHO PLAYER He rode back over the world, searching with no success. He looked high, and he looked low, but the gods were nowhere to be found. He had no luck, until he chanced upon a wise man, who told him that the gods could only be reached through prayer. So he prayed and fasted for a month, recieving no response.
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ITEMVAL1 = 3
		ECHO PLAYER Part the third:
		ECHO PLAYER And then, up in the heavens, Nirmathon, the god of adventures, heard his prayer, and became intrigued. Thus it was that Rakthaarn was visited by the gods. Full of the fire and arrogance of youth, he challenged them to a contest of wills, with immortality as the prize. But the gods, beings no fools, insisted that he stake something of equal value. So, in his arrogance, he offered forth all the energy and life from his world. And thus did the contest begin.
		ECHO PLAYER The contest raged onwards... for days and days, Rakthaarn and Nirmathon locked their wills, each struggling to overcome the other, but neither prevailing. So Raunuman, the god of mischief, becoming bored with the whole idea, poked poor Rakthaarn, disrupting his concentration and allowing his rival to win. And so it was that the gods drained the world of all its energy and life, leaving a vast Xerkataal.
		ECHO PLAYER Rakthaarn spent his remaining years wandering the wastes, in a daze. He died, and was interred here, at the heart of the world he destroyed. May those who come upon this inscription take heed of its lesson, not repeat its mistake.%c   Hereby recorded and sealed by Mantonar, scribe to the gods.
	ENDIF
ENDIF
